Here is a dumb model of financial regulation. There are two general ways fo=
r authorities to regulate financial activities. Call one =E2=80=9Crulemakin=
g.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0A regulator thinks about some financial things, decides ho=
w they should work, solicits comments from industry participants and the ge=
neral public, and writes a rule explaining in some detail how things will w=
ork. After that, everyone who does those things knows what the rules are an=
d what things they are and are not allowed to do.Call the other =E2=80=9Cre=
gulation by enforcement.=E2=80=9D The regulator doesn=E2=80=99t spend much =
time writing specific new rules, but just relies on some general old rules =
saying things like,=C2=A0you know, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use an artifice t=
o defraud.=E2=80=9D What that means can be unclear and, more to the point, =
if the regulators decide to go after you for using some artifices, your lif=
e will be unpleasant even if you ultimately win. Knowing this dynamic, the =
regulators can use enforcement actions to decide and declare what is and is=
 not allowed. Everyone goes around doing things, and then some of them get =
sued by the regulator and have to pay a bunch of money to settle the lawsui=
ts. Everyone watches those lawsuits, and each lawsuit tells everyone a bit =
more about what is and is not allowed. If the regulators sue someone for do=
ing X, and you=E2=80=99re also doing X, you stop doing X. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=
=80=99t do X=E2=80=9D has become a rule without any rulemaking. The first p=
erson to get sued for X didn=E2=80=99t know that that was the rule, though,=
 and gets in trouble and has to pay a fine.One way to think about this is t=
hat it is unfair: That person didn=E2=80=99t know X was against the rules, =
why should she get in trouble? Often though it does not feel that unfair, b=
ecause X probably does look pretty bad; it=C2=A0probably=C2=A0was=C2=A0at l=
east arguably against some general rule like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use any=
 artifices.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a little random that this person got in t=
rouble for doing X, but it=E2=80=99s not like she was totally innocent eith=
er. The people who get fined were in some gray area; they didn=E2=80=99t kn=
ow that what they were doing was=C2=A0not allowed, but they had some notice=
 that it=C2=A0might not be allowed.But another way to think about it is tha=
t regulation is expensive, and regulation by enforcement is a way to make t=
he industry pay for regulation. In rulemaking, the regulator has to put a l=
ot of expensive effort into figuring out what should be allowed; this is pa=
rticularly hard when a lot of novel activities are going on, and there is a=
 risk that the regulator will get it wrong, miss things, move too slowly, e=
tc. In regulation by enforcement, the industry has to put a lot of expensiv=
e effort into figuring out what is not allowed, and the risk of missing thi=
ngs is on the industry; the regulator gets to focus its attention on what i=
s actually happening=C2=A0and what it wants to prevent rather than theoreti=
cal generalities. More concretely, each time the industry gets a little mor=
e clarity =E2=80=94=C2=A0each time it learns a new X that is or is not agai=
nst the rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=C2=A0pays a big fine. =E2=80=9CFines are a =
cost of doing business,=E2=80=9D people complain about financial regulation=
, but perhaps sometimes it is more like=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfines are a cost of f=
iguring out what the rules are.=E2=80=9D The regulators will tell you what =
the rules are, but one at a time, and for $10 million per rule.=C2=A0If a c=
rypto startup went to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and said =
=E2=80=9Cwe want regulatory clarity about what we need to do to run crypto =
lending programs, so you should write some rules about it,=E2=80=9D the SEC=
 would say =E2=80=9Csure, we=E2=80=99ll give that some thought in like 2036=
.=E2=80=9D If it went to 50 different U.S.=C2=A0states and asked them for c=
larity it would get even more confused. If it went to the SEC and said =E2=
=80=9Clook, to speed this process along, why don=E2=80=99t we pay you $50 m=
illion to prioritize writing these rules,=E2=80=9D that would be a very bad=
 crime and it would to go prison.But BlockFi will give the SEC $50 million,=
[1] and it will give some=C2=A0states another $50 million, and  now it has =
clarity about crypto lending programs:Crypto proponents have argued for yea=
rs that regulators shouldn=E2=80=99t apply decades-old rules to the burgeon=
ing asset class. But in a move with sweeping implications for the industry,=
 at least one prominent company is now planning to register its offerings w=
ith the Securities and Exchange Commission.=C2=A0BlockFi Inc. announced on =
Monday that it=E2=80=99d seek SEC approval for accounts that pay clients hi=
gh yields for lending out their crypto as part of a record $100 million set=
tlement with federal and state securities watchdogs. The plan would give th=
e Jersey City, New Jersey-based firm the first SEC sanctioned product of it=
s kind, immediately adding pressure on competitors to follow suit. =E2=80=
=A6As part of the agreement announced by the SEC, current BlockFi customers=
 can continue to earn interest on their existing investments, but the compa=
ny must not sell the products to new American clients. The company has 60 d=
ays to seek to comply with SEC regulations and it=E2=80=99s also seeking to=
 register a new crypto-lending product that will satisfy the agency=E2=80=
=99s rules.That is from a Bloomberg article about BlockFi=E2=80=99s big new=
 plans that will give it a first-mover advantage and also about the $100 mi=
llion fine it paid. The headline is =E2=80=9CBlockFi=E2=80=99s Plans to Reg=
ister with SEC Augurs New Era for Crypto.=E2=80=9D The Wall Street Journal=
=E2=80=99s headline is =E2=80=9CBlockFi to Pay Record Penalty to Settle SEC=
 Probe of Crypto Lending Business.=E2=80=9D Both true!=C2=A0Or here is=C2=
=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Emily Chang  interviewing BlockFi Chief Executive Of=
ficer Zac Prince about the settlement, and while she starts the interview b=
y asking why BlockFi broke the law =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is after all what t=
he SEC concluded here=C2=A0(BlockFi neither admitted nor denied it) =E2=80=
=94 Prince stays on message that this settlement is about =E2=80=9Cblazing =
a path=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cfinding a regulatory construct=E2=80=9D for cr=
ypto lending. And  here=E2=80=99s this:Kristin Smith, the executive directo=
r of the Blockchain Association, said her trade group is =E2=80=9Ccommitted=
 to working with Washington to establish common-sense guardrails for indust=
ry in which to operate.=E2=80=9D She called the BlockFi settlement =E2=80=
=9Ca step forward toward that goal.=E2=80=9DI think that you can read this =
story as =E2=80=9CBlockFi did something illegal and got in trouble,=E2=80=
=9D or you can=C2=A0read it as =E2=80=9CBlockFi has worked with the SEC to =
develop=C2=A0the first U.S. regulated crypto lending product, giving it a c=
ompetitive advantage,=E2=80=9D but I do not really think you have to choose=
. BlockFi ventured out into the gray area, which got it (1) a big fine and =
(2) clarity.=C2=A0It is certainly possible that I am exaggerating here. The=
 SEC has been saying for some time that crypto yield products like this =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0in which retail customers deposit their cryptocurrency with an =
exchange, which then lends it out to institutional borrowers and pays the r=
etail depositors a fixed interest rate =E2=80=94=C2=A0are securities under =
standard interpretations of U.S. law, and I have in the past agreed=C2=A0th=
at they are pretty obviously securities. BlockFi has real lawyers and appar=
ently disagreed, but I do not think that the SEC would say that this was a =
gray area.[2] Thus the $100 million fine.It also may be an exaggeration to =
say that BlockFi has gotten a ton of clarity here, or a clear path to a leg=
al product. It still has to write a registration statement and indenture fo=
r its SEC-registered yield product, and the SEC=E2=80=99s examiners could o=
bject when it does file that statement.[3] Still it seems like both sides h=
ere think that they have found a path to compliance that works. The headlin=
e on the SEC=E2=80=99s press release is not just about the fine; it says =
=E2=80=9CBlockFi Agrees to Pay $100 Million in Penalties and Pursue Registr=
ation of its Crypto Lending Product.=E2=80=9D And the SEC=E2=80=99s order g=
oes so far as to include a picture of what it expects BlockFi=E2=80=99s leg=
al lending product to look like:That=E2=80=99s an=C2=A0approving picture; t=
hat=E2=80=99s, like, =E2=80=9Cthis thing is a thing that we could see our w=
ay to allowing.=E2=80=9D You don=E2=80=99t include a picture of BlockFi=E2=
=80=99s proposed product if you think the proposal doesn=E2=80=99t work.And=
 it is in both sides=E2=80=99 interests to make this work: BlockFi of cours=
e wants to have a profitable lending product, but the SEC also wants to dem=
onstrate that it can regulate crypto activity. =E2=80=9CWe will ban all cry=
pto activity=E2=80=9D is not, I think, a particularly viable approach for t=
he SEC to take at this point. The SEC wants to send a message along the lin=
es of =E2=80=9Clots of crypto things are securities and thus subject to sec=
urities regulation, but that=E2=80=99s fine because securities regulation i=
s totally workable for crypto things.=E2=80=9D So=C2=A0making securities re=
gulation work for a popular crypto product=C2=A0is a goal for the SEC too.W=
e are still in the very early stages of crypto regulation in the U.S., and =
if you are a crypto firm you have to think a bit about the meta-regulatory =
landscape.=C2=A0There seem to be roughly three approaches:=09Try to make yo=
urself as immune as possible to U.S. regulation by setting up abroad, runni=
ng your firm as a decentralized entity with no one for the SEC to yell at, =
staying anonymous, and doing whatever egregious things you want. So far thi=
s seems to work! Not everyone will want to move abroad and be anonymous tho=
ugh, and this approach seems to carry some big risks.=09Try to be as law-ab=
iding as possible, consult with the relevant U.S. authorities before doing =
anything adventurous, and make your case to the regulators for rules that y=
ou think will be good for crypto. This sounds good, but I am not sure it=C2=
=A0works. When Coinbase Global Inc., a U.S. public company, wanted to launc=
h a lending product like BlockFi=E2=80=99s, the SEC   told it not to and it=
 didn=E2=80=99t. Last October=C2=A0Coinbase put out=C2=A0an ambitious=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9COperational Framework of the Digital Asset Policy Proposal,=E2=80=
=9D which it clearly hoped would spark a conversation in Washington about h=
ow best to build a new crypto regulatory framework for crypto; I don=E2=80=
=99t think anyone has mentioned it since.=C2=A0When Facebook (now Meta Plat=
forms Inc.) wanted to launch a stablecoin, it put on a big show of working =
with regulators, which gave regulators lots of chances to say no, which the=
y did, and now=C2=A0Facebook=E2=80=99s stablecoin dream is dead. =E2=80=9CT=
here is a certain drunk-under-the-lamppost element to current U.S. crypto r=
egulation,=E2=80=9D   I wrote recently: =E2=80=9CIf you incorporate a compa=
ny in the U.S. and walk into the SEC=E2=80=99s office and ask =E2=80=98hey =
what are we allowed to do,=E2=80=99 the answer is =E2=80=98almost nothing.=
=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=09Try to be, you know, a medium amount of law-abiding. K=
eep doing stuff, stake out aggressive but plausible legal positions, and wh=
en the SEC complains be quick to settle. =E2=80=9CMove fast and break thing=
s,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cbetter to ask forgiveness than permission,=E2=80=9D et=
c. Each time the SEC says you broke the law, you get a little more informat=
ion about=C2=A0what the law is, and each time you negotiate a settlement, y=
ou get an opportunity to=C2=A0influence the law. This is expensive, but may=
be it works? Nothing in this column is ever legal advice, and in particular=
 I hate to say=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cmaybe you should break the law a little bit.=
=E2=80=9D But, uh, what do you conclude from this?Here=E2=80=99s what SEC C=
ommissioner Hester Peirce concluded, in dissenting from the settlement:We o=
ften tell companies wanting to offer products that could implicate the secu=
rities laws to =E2=80=9Ccome in and talk to us.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0To make that=
 invitation meaningful, however, we need to commit to working with these co=
mpanies to craft sensible, timely, and achievable regulatory paths. =C2=A0W=
orking with an earnest desire to reach a prudent, properly calibrated regul=
atory outcome is important for a number of reasons. =C2=A0First, these prod=
ucts matter to people. =C2=A0A program that allows people=E2=80=94and not j=
ust affluent people=E2=80=94to keep their crypto assets, while still earnin=
g a return is valuable to many Americans, as evidenced by the programs=E2=
=80=99 popularity in the United States to date. =C2=A0The investor protecti=
on objective of today=E2=80=99s settlement will be poorly served if retail =
investors are ultimately shut out from participation in these products. =C2=
=A0Second, our process speaks volumes about our integrity as a regulator. =
=C2=A0Inviting people to come in and talk to us only to drag them through a=
 difficult, lengthy, unproductive, and labyrinthine regulatory process cast=
s the Commission in a bad light and thus makes us a less effective regulato=
r. =C2=A0Third, a company that tries to do the right thing should be met ac=
ross the table by a regulator that tries to get to a sensible result in a r=
easonable timeframe. =C2=A0For the sake of the American public, our own rep=
utation, and the companies that heed our call to come in and talk to us, we=
 need to do better than we have so far at accommodating innovation through =
thoughtful use of the exemptive authority Congress gave us.I dunno, BlockFi=
 seems weirdly happy that it talked to the SEC. But it was an expensive con=
versation.
