      Block trades
   =20
 =20
Trading desks at investment banks are, famously, in the moving business, no=
t the storage business. If you want to sell a big block of stock, an invest=
ment bank will not want to own it; they are just not set up to own big bloc=
ks of stock. But they are in the moving=C2=A0business, and if you come to t=
hem looking to sell a big block of stock they will buy it from you, both be=
cause that is how they make money (buying it from you and then reselling it=
 at a higher price) and more deeply because that is their=C2=A0job and thei=
r customers won=E2=80=99t like them if they say no. They are in the busines=
s of standing ready to buy or sell stocks or bonds from their customers, an=
d if they said no a lot they wouldn=E2=80=99t be in that business anymore.A=
nd so the bank is in the business of buying=C2=A0stocks and bonds and then =
quickly turning around to resell them.[4] It does not want to own the stock=
s, but does not want to say no to buying them. So it has to have a lot of c=
onfidence that it can resell them, preferably at a higher price than it pai=
d. For small stock trades this is essentially a statistical question and a =
computer answers it, but for large blocks of stock it is a harder question.=
 When you call the bank asking it to buy $500 million of Stock X, the goal =
is for the bank=E2=80=99s Stock X trader to be so knowledgeable about the m=
arket for Stock X, to have so much insight into who is looking to add to or=
 subtract from their Stock X positions and what the drivers of demand are, =
that she can instantly put a price on it that is competitive (high enough t=
hat you will sell to her) and yet profitable (low enough that she=E2=80=99l=
l be able to resell=C2=A0quickly at a profit). She gets this knowledge by l=
ong practical experience, by watching the tape, and by talking to investors=
 (and analysts and salespeople) all day; this is her business; her whole jo=
b is knowing who is looking to buy and sell what. So when you call her for =
a price she thinks =E2=80=9CI bet Hedge Fund A will buy $100 million of thi=
s down 2% and Asset Manager B is looking to add about $200 million down 1.5=
%=E2=80=9D and keeps going down the list until she has a clear picture of h=
ow she will sell the stock and at what price. And then she gives you a bid.=
But this is hard and risky; she might think that Hedge Fund A wants Stock X=
 but actually it bought a bunch yesterday and is all full up. So it will ma=
ke her life easier if she can say =E2=80=9Chang on a minute,=E2=80=9D put y=
ou on hold, and go call some potential buyers to see if they=E2=80=99re int=
erested before giving you a price. The best way to get market knowledge is =
sometimes to ask directly.Sometimes some version of this is allowed, but of=
ten it is not.=C2=A0For instance:Federal investigators are probing the busi=
ness of block trading on Wall Street, examining whether bankers might have =
improperly tipped hedge-fund clients in advance of large share sales, accor=
ding to people familiar with the situation.The Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission sent subpoenas to firms including Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs G=
roup Inc. as well as several hedge funds, asking for trading records and in=
formation about the investors=E2=80=99 communications with bankers, some of=
 the people said. The Justice Department also is investigating the matter, =
some of the people said. =E2=80=A6Investigators are looking at whether bank=
ers improperly alerted favored clients to the sales before they were public=
ly disclosed and whether the funds benefited from the information=E2=80=94f=
or example by shorting the shares in question. (In a short sale, an investo=
r sells borrowed stock in hopes of buying it back at a lower price later an=
d pocketing the difference.)Shares of companies selling stock often fall be=
cause of an increase in supply hitting the market=E2=80=94and they do so fr=
equently in the hours before a big block is sold, a phenomenon that has lon=
g raised questions on Wall Street.Some of the funds that received subpoenas=
 act as =E2=80=9Cliquidity providers=E2=80=9D to Wall Street firms, accordi=
ng to some of the people, standing by to purchase large amounts of stock or=
 other securities, including those that have few interested buyers.The rule=
s governing when and how Wall Street firms can tell clients about coming bl=
ock trades are murky. In some cases, there are questions around whether div=
ulging certain information or acting on it is improper or illegal, lawyers =
say.=E2=80=9CBlock trades=E2=80=9D can mean a number of different things, b=
ut often it means a trade in which=C2=A0the company itself=C2=A0sells a big=
 block of stock. Instead of doing a traditional offering (in which it annou=
nces the deal and banks spend a day marketing it, then come to the company =
with a price), it can get a bank to commit to a price (typically just after=
 the market closes at 4 p.m., at a=C2=A0discount of a few percent to the cl=
osing price); the bank will try to find buyers after the close and be out o=
f the block by the time the market opens in the morning. But if it can=E2=
=80=99t find buyers, that's the bank=E2=80=99s problem. Sometimes a company=
 will just go to its favorite bank and ask for a price, but often the compa=
ny will have multiple banks bid on the block and take the highest price.Gen=
erally the banks will have some advance notice =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company m=
ight tell them at 10 a.m. that it wants bids for a block at 4 p.m. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and the bank will spend some time thinking about the right price. =
One way to do that thinking would be to call up a bunch of hedge funds and =
say =E2=80=9Chey if we did a block for Company X how much would you want an=
d at what price,=E2=80=9D though that is very much frowned upon; the block =
trade is material nonpublic information. Thus the investigation.By the way,=
 there are lots of ways for this information to leak, beyond the obvious on=
e of the banks just telling everyone. Here are a few:=09A bank considering =
bidding on a block might call up some investors and ask them some general q=
uestions. =E2=80=9CHey how are you feeling about the tech sector today,=E2=
=80=9D the bank might ask. A smart hedge fund that is following the sector =
might say =E2=80=9Caha, you have block coming for Tech Company X=E2=80=9D a=
nd short the stock.=C2=A0=09A bank considering a block trade might=C2=A0wal=
l-cross a few investors, asking them to agree not to trade in the company=
=E2=80=99s stock for 24 hours; then the bank can feel more comfortable aski=
ng the investors about the stock without worrying that it is tipping them. =
But this is a fraught process. =E2=80=9CWe would like to talk to you about =
a tech name, would you take a wall-cross,=E2=80=9D the bank might ask, and =
the hedge fund might say =E2=80=9Caha you=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0have a block=
 coming for Tech Company X,=E2=80=9D decline the wall-cross=C2=A0and short =
the stock.=09The investor might=C2=A0agree=C2=A0not to trade Stock X =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but what if it shorts Stock Y, a correlated stock in the same sect=
or, as a hedge? That has always been a bit murky,=C2=A0but recently the SEC=
   has gone after this sort of =E2=80=9Cshadow trading,=E2=80=9D in which y=
ou use inside information about one company to trade a correlated stock. Th=
at case was about a corporate insider using information about his own compa=
ny to shadow trade a competitor, but you could imagine the SEC   extending =
the theory to hedge funds in this sort of scenario.
