   =20
 =20
If I ran a hedge fund and had a time machine, what I would probably do woul=
d be buy Tesla=C2=A0Inc. stock on Jan. 1, 2020, and then nothing else. I me=
an, first I would negotiate really good investor agreements with long locku=
ps, so that if any of my investors called me and said =E2=80=9Cwait is your=
 hedge fund=E2=80=99s entire strategy just owning Tesla stock?=E2=80=9D I c=
ould say =E2=80=9Cyep=E2=80=9D and hang up without them withdrawing their m=
oney. But then I would buy as much Tesla as I could get, tell everyone to g=
o home, lock the doors and come back at the end of the year.=C2=A0Tesla was=
 up a ludicrous 743% in 2020, which would put me among the all-time greats =
of hedge fund performance. My performance fees would be=C2=A020% or whateve=
r of 743%, meaning that at the end of the year I would be able to pay mysel=
f=C2=A0more than all of the money=C2=A0my investors put in at the beginning=
 of the year, and they would be thrilled about it because they were up like=
 600% net of fees. And then I=E2=80=99d go back to them, ask for an even lo=
nger and stricter lockup, move all the money into GameStop Corp. for 2021[5=
] and go back to the beach.If you had a hedge fund and a time machine, you =
could probably find=C2=A0better=C2=A0trades.[6] Tesla had more than a 50% d=
rawdown=C2=A0between mid-February and mid-March 2020; if you had done a lit=
tle active trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0even just selling in February and buying =
back in March =E2=80=94=C2=A0you could have had, like, a 1,500% return inst=
ead of 743%. My colleague John Authers runs a time-machine-driven paper hed=
ge fund called  Hindsight Capital, which regularly finds great trades that =
probably have a higher Sharpe ratio than mine and are certainly easier to e=
xplain to clients. Mine, however, maximizes the ratio of returns to=C2=A0ef=
fort. I buy one stock and forget about it. I do not do a ton of digging to =
identify that stock, either; my investment process here consisted of (1) as=
king myself =E2=80=9Cwhat is the stock that has most famously gone up a ton=
 recently=E2=80=9D and (2) looking at historical prices on Bloomberg to get=
 a number to write down. It took me two minutes. Of course=C2=A0I cannot=C2=
=A0actually=C2=A0turn this insight into billions of dollars because I do no=
t have a time machine but, you know, imagine how cool it would be if I did.=
 I=E2=80=99d get to spend all year at the beach, and at the end of the year=
 I=E2=80=99d go buy myself five beach houses.=C2=A0Meanwhile actual hedge f=
und managers, limited by their own lack of time machines (and, in most case=
s, of  really strict lockups), have to go around making sensible trades and=
 hedging and diversifying and trying to capture uncorrelated returns and al=
l that stuff, and it ends up being a hard and demanding job, even though in=
 theory you could do the job by just buying one thing and holding it, if it=
=E2=80=99s the right thing. Sometimes it works like that though:Karthik Sar=
ma outearned Steve Cohen last year.The little-known hedge fund manager made=
 an estimated $2 billion in 2021, mostly thanks to an 11-year-old wager on =
Avis Budget Group Inc., a bet that paid off handsomely as the stock soared =
456%. ...At SRS Investment Management, he avoids the hefty leverage many ot=
her funds embrace, and runs a much more robust short book. Moreover, he isn=
=E2=80=99t afraid to go big on a single investment =E2=80=94 and hang on fo=
r as long as it takes.That helps explain how Sarma appeared near the very t=
op of Bloomberg=E2=80=99s 2021 ranking of hedge fund earners, only slightly=
 outdone by Citadel=E2=80=99s Ken Griffin and TCI Fund Management=E2=80=99s=
 Chris Hohn. SRS owns about 50% of Avis through common stock and swaps, hel=
ping to roughly triple Sarma=E2=80=99s net worth to $3 billion, according t=
o an analysis by the Bloomberg Billionaires Index, and rewarding investors =
in his flagship fund with a 35% gain. =E2=80=A6The Avis wager is unusual fo=
r him. It=E2=80=99s the largest and longest he=E2=80=99s made, and the only=
 one where he -- or anyone else at the firm -- sits on a company=E2=80=99s =
board. Hedge funds generally avoid board seats because that limits when the=
y can buy and sell shares. =E2=80=A6The jump in Sarma=E2=80=99s net worth w=
as particularly large because the investment is spread across several of th=
e firm=E2=80=99s portfolios, and he personally owns about 90% of one fund t=
hat only holds the Avis stake.Imagine being Sarma and sitting down to write=
 your investor letters for 2021. You start with the flagship fund: =E2=80=
=9CI am happy to report that we were up 35% this year. Our long positions d=
id well, led by Avis Budget, which was up 456%. On the short side, our best=
 bet was ...=E2=80=9D and you=E2=80=99d go on in that vein, analyzing your =
hits and misses, thinking about what you got right and what you could have =
done better. And then you go on to write the letters for your other funds, =
and you get to the Just Holding Avis fund, which does have some money that =
is not yours, so I guess those investors expect a letter. And you write =E2=
=80=9Cthe Just Holding Avis fund was up 456% this year (365% net of fees), =
on the back of very strong performance by Avis, which was also up 456%. It =
was a good year to be invested entirely in Avis stock,[7] and I=E2=80=99m g=
lad we were. I guess that=E2=80=99s it?=E2=80=9DAnyway Sarma is No. 3 on =
=E2=80=9CBloomberg=E2=80=99s 2021 ranking of hedge fund earners=E2=80=9D; N=
os. 1 and 2 are Citadel=E2=80=99s Ken Griffin and TCI Fund Management=E2=80=
=99s Chris Hohn. Many of the people on the list =E2=80=94=C2=A0there=E2=80=
=99s also Izzy Englander of Millennium, Jim Simons of Renaissance Technolog=
ies, Steve Cohen of Point72, David Shaw of D.E. Shaw, Ray Dalio of Bridgewa=
ter, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0run big institutions with multiple strategies that=
 try to use rigorous processes to generate uncorrelated alpha; they also ha=
ve enormous amounts of assets under management and so can make a lot in fee=
s. Meanwhile Sarma=E2=80=99s on the list because=C2=A0he bought a lot of on=
e stock and that stock went up a lot. Just seems more pleasant, you know?
