<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">BlockFi</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a dumb model of financial regu=
lation. There are two general ways for authorities to regulate financial ac=
tivities. Call one =E2=80=9Crulemaking.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0A regulator thinks ab=
out some financial things, decides how they should work, solicits comments =
from industry participants and the general public, and writes a rule explai=
ning in some detail how things will work. After that, everyone who does tho=
se things knows what the rules are and what things they are and are not all=
owed to do.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Call the other =E2=80=9Cregulat=
ion by enforcement.=E2=80=9D The regulator doesn=E2=80=99t spend much time =
writing specific new rules, but just relies on some general old rules sayin=
g things like,=C2=A0you know, =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use an artifice to def=
raud.=E2=80=9D What that means can be unclear and, more to the point, if th=
e regulators decide to go after you for using some artifices, your life wil=
l be unpleasant even if you ultimately win. Knowing this dynamic, the regul=
ators can use enforcement actions to decide and declare what is and is not =
allowed. Everyone goes around doing things, and then some of them get sued =
by the regulator and have to pay a bunch of money to settle the lawsuits. E=
veryone watches those lawsuits, and each lawsuit tells everyone a bit more =
about what is and is not allowed. If the regulators sue someone for doing X=
, and you=E2=80=99re also doing X, you stop doing X. =E2=80=9CDon=E2=80=99t=
 do X=E2=80=9D has become a rule without any rulemaking. The first person t=
o get sued for X didn=E2=80=99t know that that was the rule, though, and ge=
ts in trouble and has to pay a fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One wa=
y to think about this is that it is unfair: That person didn=E2=80=99t know=
 X was against the rules, why should she get in trouble? Often though it do=
es not feel <em>that</em> unfair, because X probably does look pretty bad; =
it=C2=A0probably=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>at least arguably against some gene=
ral rule like =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t use any artifices.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=
=99s a little random that this person got in trouble for doing X, but it=E2=
=80=99s not like she was totally innocent either. The people who get fined =
were in some gray area; they didn=E2=80=99t <em>know</em> that what they we=
re doing was=C2=A0not allowed, but they had some notice that it=C2=A0<em>mi=
ght</em> not be allowed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But another way to=
 think about it is that regulation is expensive, and regulation by enforcem=
ent is a way to <em>make the industry pay for regulation</em>. In rulemakin=
g, the regulator has to put a lot of expensive effort into figuring out wha=
t should be allowed; this is particularly hard when a lot of novel activiti=
es are going on, and there is a risk that the regulator will get it wrong, =
miss things, move too slowly, etc. In regulation by enforcement, the indust=
ry has to put a lot of expensive effort into figuring out what is not allow=
ed, and the risk of missing things is on the industry; the regulator gets t=
o focus its attention on <em>what is actually happening=C2=A0</em>and what =
it wants to prevent rather than theoretical generalities. More concretely, =
each time the industry gets a little more clarity =E2=80=94=C2=A0each time =
it learns a new X that is or is not against the rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=C2=
=A0<em>pays a big fine</em>. =E2=80=9CFines are a cost of doing business,=
=E2=80=9D people complain about financial regulation, but perhaps sometimes=
 it is more like=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfines are a cost of figuring out what the ru=
les are.=E2=80=9D The regulators will tell you what the rules are, but one =
at a time, and for $10 million per rule.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">If a crypto startup went to the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission=
 and said =E2=80=9Cwe want regulatory clarity about what we need to do to r=
un crypto lending programs, so you should write some rules about it,=E2=80=
=9D the SEC would say =E2=80=9Csure, we=E2=80=99ll give that some thought i=
n like 2036.=E2=80=9D If it went to 50 different U.S.=C2=A0states and asked=
 <em>them </em>for clarity it would get even more confused. If it went to t=
he SEC and said =E2=80=9Clook, to speed this process along, why don=E2=80=
=99t we pay you $50 million to prioritize writing these rules,=E2=80=9D tha=
t would be a very bad crime and it would to go prison.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">But BlockFi will give the SEC $50 million,[1] and it will give =
some=C2=A0states another $50 million, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/26719940.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTQvYmxvY2tmaS1zLXBsYW5zLXRvLXJlZ2lzdGVyLXdpdG=
gtc2VjLWF1Z3Vycy1uZXctZXJhLWZvci1jcnlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVR=
kYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE1=
JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4cc8a263" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> now it has clarity about crypto lending programs</a>:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto proponents have argued for years that regul=
ators shouldn=E2=80=99t apply decades-old rules to the burgeoning asset cla=
ss. But in a move with sweeping implications for the industry, at least one=
 prominent company is now planning to register its offerings with the Secur=
ities and Exchange Commission.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BlockF=
i Inc. announced on Monday that it=E2=80=99d seek SEC approval for accounts=
 that pay clients high yields for lending out their crypto as part of a rec=
ord $100 million settlement with federal and state securities watchdogs. Th=
e plan would give the Jersey City, New Jersey-based firm the first SEC sanc=
tioned product of its kind, immediately adding pressure on competitors to f=
ollow suit. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As part of the agreem=
ent announced by the SEC, current BlockFi customers can continue to earn in=
terest on their existing investments, but the company must not sell the pro=
ducts to new American clients. The company has 60 days to seek to comply wi=
th SEC regulations and it=E2=80=99s also seeking to register a new crypto-l=
ending product that will satisfy the agency=E2=80=99s rules.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from a Bloomberg article about Block=
Fi=E2=80=99s big new plans that will give it a first-mover advantage and al=
so about the $100 million fine it paid. The headline is =E2=80=9CBlockFi=E2=
=80=99s Plans to Register with SEC Augurs New Era for Crypto.=E2=80=9D The =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26719940.285603/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9ibG9ja2ZpLXRvLXBheS1yZWNvcmQtcGVuYWx0e=
S10by1zZXR0bGUtc2VjLXByb2JlLW9mLWNyeXB0by1sZW5kaW5nLWJ1c2luZXNzLTExNjQ0ODU0=
NDAw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3418a856" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal=E2=80=
=99s headline</a> is =E2=80=9CBlockFi to Pay Record Penalty to Settle SEC P=
robe of Crypto Lending Business.=E2=80=9D Both true!=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Or here is=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Emily Chang <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26719940.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL3ZpZGVvcy8yMDIyLTAyLTE0L2Jsb2NrZmktdG8tcGF5LTEw=
MC1taWxsaW9uLXRvLXNlYy1vbi1jcnlwdG8tbGVuZGluZy12aWRlbz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE1MjJ=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yMjAyMTUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf1f=
b306" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> interviewing BlockFi Chief Executive Officer Zac Prince</a> =
about the settlement, and while she starts the interview by asking why Bloc=
kFi broke the law =E2=80=94=C2=A0which is after all what the SEC concluded =
here=C2=A0(BlockFi neither admitted nor denied it) =E2=80=94 Prince stays o=
n message that this settlement is about =E2=80=9Cblazing a path=E2=80=9D an=
d =E2=80=9Cfinding a regulatory construct=E2=80=9D for crypto lending. And =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26719940.285603/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTQvYmxvY2tma=
S1zLXBsYW5zLXRvLXJlZ2lzdGVyLXdpdGgtc2VjLWF1Z3Vycy1uZXctZXJhLWZvci1jcnlwdG8_=
Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5=
ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cC4cc8a263" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p><blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kristin Smith, the executive director of the B=
lockchain Association, said her trade group is =E2=80=9Ccommitted to workin=
g with Washington to establish common-sense guardrails for industry in whic=
h to operate.=E2=80=9D She called the BlockFi settlement =E2=80=9Ca step fo=
rward toward that goal.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I think that you can read this story as =E2=80=9CBlockFi did something i=
llegal and got in trouble,=E2=80=9D or you can=C2=A0read it as =E2=80=9CBlo=
ckFi has worked with the SEC to develop=C2=A0the first U.S. regulated crypt=
o lending product, giving it a competitive advantage,=E2=80=9D but I do not=
 really think you have to choose. BlockFi ventured out into the gray area, =
which got it (1) a big fine and (2) clarity.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">It is certainly possible that I am exaggerating here. The SEC has b=
een saying for some time that crypto yield products like this =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in which retail customers deposit their cryptocurrency with an exchange,=
 which then lends it out to institutional borrowers and pays the retail dep=
ositors a fixed interest rate =E2=80=94=C2=A0are securities under standard =
interpretations of U.S. law, and I have in the past <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26719940.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDgvbGVuZGluZy1iaXRjb2lucy1pcy10=
cmlja3k_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc284326c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">agreed</a>=C2=A0that they are pre=
tty obviously securities. BlockFi has real lawyers and apparently disagreed=
, but I do not think that the SEC would say that this was a gray area.[2] T=
hus the $100 million fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It also may be a=
n exaggeration to say that BlockFi has gotten a ton of clarity here, or a c=
lear path to a legal product. It still has to write a registration statemen=
t and indenture for its SEC-registered yield product, and the SEC=E2=80=99s=
 examiners could object when it does file that statement.[3] Still it seems=
 like both sides here think that they have found a path to compliance that =
works. The headline on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/26719940.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMj=
AyMi0yNg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35dad803" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC=E2=80=99s press=
 release</a> is not just about the fine; it says =E2=80=9CBlockFi Agrees to=
 Pay $100 Million in Penalties and Pursue Registration of its Crypto Lendin=
g Product.=E2=80=9D And the SEC=E2=80=99s order goes so far as to include a=
 picture of what it expects BlockFi=E2=80=99s legal lending product to look=
 like:</p><!--[if mso]>
