<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Block trades</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trading desks at investment banks are,=
 famously, in the moving business, not the storage business. If you want to=
 sell a big block of stock, an investment bank will not want to <em>own </e=
m>it; they are just not set up to own big blocks of stock. But they are in =
the moving=C2=A0<em>business</em>, and if you come to them looking to sell =
a big block of stock they will buy it from you, both because that is how th=
ey make money (buying it from you and then reselling it at a higher price) =
and more deeply because that is their=C2=A0<em>job</em> and their customers=
 won=E2=80=99t like them if they say no. They are in the business of standi=
ng ready to buy or sell stocks or bonds from their customers, and if they s=
aid no a lot they wouldn=E2=80=99t be in that business anymore.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the bank is in the business of buying=C2=A0stoc=
ks and bonds and then quickly turning around to resell them.[4] It does not=
 want to own the stocks, but does not want to say no to buying them. So it =
has to have a lot of confidence that it can resell them, preferably at a hi=
gher price than it paid. For small stock trades this is essentially a stati=
stical question and a computer answers it, but for large blocks of stock it=
 is a harder question. When you call the bank asking it to buy $500 million=
 of Stock X, the goal is for the bank=E2=80=99s Stock X trader to be so kno=
wledgeable about the market for Stock X, to have so much insight into who i=
s looking to add to or subtract from their Stock X positions and what the d=
rivers of demand are, that she can instantly put a price on it that is comp=
etitive (high enough that you will sell to her) and yet profitable (low eno=
ugh that she=E2=80=99ll be able to resell=C2=A0quickly at a profit). She ge=
ts this knowledge by long practical experience, by watching the tape, and b=
y talking to investors (and analysts and salespeople) all day; this is her =
business; her whole job is knowing who is looking to buy and sell what. So =
when you call her for a price she thinks =E2=80=9CI bet Hedge Fund A will b=
uy $100 million of this down 2% and Asset Manager B is looking to add about=
 $200 million down 1.5%=E2=80=9D and keeps going down the list until she ha=
s a clear picture of how she will sell the stock and at what price. And the=
n she gives you a bid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is hard and=
 risky; she might think that Hedge Fund A wants Stock X but actually it bou=
ght a bunch yesterday and is all full up. So it will make her life easier i=
f she can say =E2=80=9Chang on a minute,=E2=80=9D put you on hold, and go c=
all some potential buyers to see if they=E2=80=99re interested before givin=
g you a price. The best way to get market knowledge is sometimes to ask dir=
ectly.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes some version of this is al=
lowed, but often it is not.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/26719940.285603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yZWd1=
bGF0b3JzLXByb2JlLWJsb2NrLXRyYWRpbmctYXQtbW9yZ2FuLXN0YW5sZXktZ29sZG1hbi1vdGh=
lci13YWxsLXN0cmVldC1maXJtcy0xMTY0NDg3NTQ0OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8f88ea=
52" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">For instance</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Federal investigators are probing the business of block trading on Wall Str=
eet, examining whether bankers might have improperly tipped hedge-fund clie=
nts in advance of large share sales, according to people familiar with the =
situation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission sent subpoenas to firms including Morgan Stanley and Goldman Sachs G=
roup Inc. as well as several hedge funds, asking for trading records and in=
formation about the investors=E2=80=99 communications with bankers, some of=
 the people said. The Justice Department also is investigating the matter, =
some of the people said. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investig=
ators are looking at whether bankers improperly alerted favored clients to =
the sales before they were publicly disclosed and whether the funds benefit=
ed from the information=E2=80=94for example by shorting the shares in quest=
ion. (In a short sale, an investor sells borrowed stock in hopes of buying =
it back at a lower price later and pocketing the difference.)</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shares of companies selling stock often fall because o=
f an increase in supply hitting the market=E2=80=94and they do so frequentl=
y in the hours before a big block is sold, a phenomenon that has long raise=
d questions on Wall Street.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the fun=
ds that received subpoenas act as =E2=80=9Cliquidity providers=E2=80=9D to =
Wall Street firms, according to some of the people, standing by to purchase=
 large amounts of stock or other securities, including those that have few =
interested buyers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rules governing when=
 and how Wall Street firms can tell clients about coming block trades are m=
urky. In some cases, there are questions around whether divulging certain i=
nformation or acting on it is improper or illegal, lawyers say.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CBlock trades=E2=80=9D can mean a=
 number of different things, but often it means a trade in which=C2=A0<em>t=
he company itself=C2=A0</em>sells a big block of stock. Instead of doing a =
traditional offering (in which it announces the deal and banks spend a day =
marketing it, then come to the company with a price), it can get a bank to =
commit to a price (typically just after the market closes at 4 p.m., at a=
=C2=A0discount of a few percent to the closing price); the bank will try to=
 find buyers after the close and be out of the block by the time the market=
 opens in the morning. But if it can=E2=80=99t find buyers, that's the bank=
=E2=80=99s problem. Sometimes a company will just go to its favorite bank a=
nd ask for a price, but often the company will have multiple banks bid on t=
he block and take the highest price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Genera=
lly the banks will have some advance notice =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company migh=
t tell them at 10 a.m. that it wants bids for a block at 4 p.m. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and the bank will spend some time thinking about the right price. One=
 way to do that thinking would be to call up a bunch of hedge funds and say=
 =E2=80=9Chey if we did a block for Company X how much would you want and a=
